brother brother dogma dogma etc are also provided single form of noun are also provided the gender of singular pronoun can be chosen for example they it or she or he or they pronunciation based a an selection is provided for all english word and most initialisms it is also possible to inflect numeral to ordinal st nd rd and to english word one two three in generating these inflection inflect py follows the oxford english dictionary and the guideline in fowler s modern english usage preferring the former where the two disagree the module is built around standard british spelling but is designed to cope with common american variant a well slang jargon and other english dialect are not explicitly catered for where two or more inflected form exist for a single word typically a classical form and a modern form inflect py prefers the more common form typically the modern one unless classical processing ha been specified see modern v classical inflection all of the plural plural inflection method take the word to be inflected a their first argument and return the corresponding inflection note that all such method expect the singular form of the word the result of passing a plural form are undefined and unlikely to be correct similarly the si singular inflection method expects the plural form of the word the plural method also take an optional second argument which indicates the grammatical number of the word or of another word with which the word being inflected must agree if the number argument is supplied and is not or one or a or some other adjective that implies the singular the plural form of the word is returned if the number argument doe indicate singularity the uninflected word itself is returned if the number argument is omitted the plural form is returned unconditionally the si method take a second argument in a similar fashion if it is some form of the number or is omitted the singular form is returned otherwise the plural is returned unaltered the various method of inflect engine are plural noun word count none the method plural noun take a singular english noun or pronoun and return it plural pronoun in the nominative i we and accusative me u case are handled a are possessive pronoun mine ours plural verb word count none the method plural verb take the singular form of a conjugated verb that is one which is already in the correct person and mood and return the corresponding plural conjugation plural adj word count none the method plural adj take the singular form of certain type of adjective and return the corresponding plural form adjective that are correctly handled include numerical adjective a some demonstrative adjective this these that those and possessive my our cat s cat child s childrens etc plural word count none the method plural take a singular english noun pronoun verb or adjective and return it plural form where a word ha more than one inflection depending on it part of speech for example the noun thought inflects to thought the verb thought to thought the singular noun sense is preferred to the singular verb sense hence plural knife will return knife knife having been treated a a singular noun whereas plural knife will return knife knife having been treated a a rd person singular verb the inherent ambiguity of such case suggests that where the part of speech is known plural noun plural verb and plural adj should be used in preference to plural singular noun word count none the method singular noun take a plural english noun or pronoun and return it singular pronoun in the nominative we i and accusative u me case are handled a are possessive pronoun ours mine when third person singular pronoun are returned they take the neuter gender by default they it description: the aim of the wrapt module is to provide a transparent object proxy for python which can be used a the basis for the construction of function wrapper and decorator function the wrapt module focus very much on correctness it therefore go way beyond existing mechanism such a functools wrap to ensure that decorator preserve introspectability signature type checking ability etc the decorator that can be constructed using this module will work in far more scenario than typical decorator and provide more predictable and consistent behaviour to ensure that the overhead is a minimal a possible a c extension module is used for performance critical component an automatic fallback to a pure python implementation is also provided where a target system doe not have a compiler to allow the c extension to be compiled for further information on the wrapt module see http wrapt readthedocs org to implement your decorator you need to first define a wrapper function this will be called each time a decorated function is called the wrapper function need to take four positional argument wrapped the wrapped function which in turn need to be called by your wrapper function instance the object to which the wrapped function wa bound when it wa called args the list of positional argument supplied when the decorated function wa called kwargs the dictionary of keyword argument supplied when the decorated function wa called the wrapper function would do whatever it need to but would usually in turn call the wrapped function that is passed in via the wrapped argument the decorator wrapt decorator then need to be applied to the wrapper function to convert it into a decorator which can in turn be applied to other function if you wish to implement a decorator which accepts argument then wrap the definition of the decorator in a function closure any argument supplied to the outer function when the decorator is applied will be available to the inner wrapper when the wrapped function is called when applied to a normal function or static method the wrapper function when called will be passed none a the instance argument when applied to an instance method the wrapper function when called will be passed the instance of the class the method is being called on a the instance argument this will be the case even when the instance method wa called explicitly via the class and the instance passed a the first argument that is the instance will never be passed a part of args when applied to a class method the wrapper function when called will be passed the class type a the instance argument when applied to a class the wrapper function when called will be passed none a the instance argument the wrapped argument in this case will be the class the above rule can be summarised with the following example using these check it is therefore possible to create a universal decorator that can be applied in all situation it is no longer necessary to create different variant of decorator for normal function and instance method or use additional wrapper to convert a function decorator into one that will work for instance method in all case the wrapped function passed to the wrapper function is called in the same way with args and kwargs being passed the instance argument doesn t need to be used in calling the wrapped function full source code for the wrapt module including documentation file and unit test can be obtained from github http github com grahamdumpleton wrapt

description: python magic is a python interface to the libmagic file type identification library libmagic identifies file type by checking their header according to a predefined list of file type this functionality is exposed to the command line by the unix command file there is also a magic class that provides more direct control including overriding the magic database file and turning on character encoding detection this is not recommended for general use in particular it s not safe for sharing across multiple thread and will fail throw if this is attempted you can also combine the flag option the current stable version of python magic is available on pypi and can be installed by running pip install python magic other source this module is a simple wrapper around the libmagic c library and that must be installed a well you ll need dlls for libmagic julian r maintains a pypi package with the dlls you can fetch it with magicexception could not find any magic file some installation of libmagic do not correctly point to their magic database file try specifying the path to the file explicitly in the constructor magic magic magic file path to magic file windowserror error is not a valid win application attempting to run the bit libmagic dll in a bit build of python will fail with this error here are bit build of libmagic for window http github com pidydx libmagicwin newer version can be found here http github com nscaife file window windowserror exception access violation writing x this may indicate you are mixing window python and cygwin python make sure your libmagic and python build are consistent python magic is a thin layer over the libmagic c library historically most bug that have been reported against python magic are actually bug in libmagic libmagic bug can be reported on their tracker here http bug astron com my view page php if you re not sure where the bug lie feel free to file an issue on github and i can triage it to run the test across a variety of linux distribution depends on docker to run test locally across all available python version to run against a specific python version the python binding shipped with libmagic use a module name that conflict with this package to work around this python magic includes a compatibility layer for the libmagic api see compat md for a guide to libmagic python magic compatibility minor version bump should be backwards compatible major bump are not written by adam hupp in for a project that never got off the ground it originally used swig for the c library binding but switched to ctypes once that wa part of the python standard library you can contact me via my website or github python magic is distributed under the mit license see the included license file for detail i am providing code in the repository to you under an open source license because this is my personal repository the license you receive to my code is from me and not my employer facebook

description: schema is a library for validating python data structure such a those obtained from config file form external service or command line parsing converted from json yaml or something else to python data type here is a quick example to get a feeling of schema validating a list of entry with personal information if data is valid schema validate will return the validated data optionally converted with use call see below if data is invalid schema will raise schemaerror exception if you just want to check that the data is valid schema is valid data will return true or false use pip or easy install alternatively you can just drop schema py file into your project it is self contained schema is tested with python and pypy schema follows semantic versioning if schema encounter a type such a int str object etc it will check if the corresponding piece of data is an instance of that type otherwise it will raise schemaerror if schema encounter a callable function class or object with call method it will call it and if it return value evaluates to true it will continue validating else it will raise schemaerror if schema encounter an object with method validate it will run this method on corresponding data a data obj validate data this method may raise schemaerror exception which will tell schema that that piece of data is invalid otherwise it will continue validating an example of validatable is regex that try to match a string or a buffer with the given regular expression itself a a string buffer or compiled regex sre pattern for a more general case you can use use for creating such object use help to use a function or type to convert a value while validating it dropping the detail use is basically sometimes you need to transform and validate part of data but keep original data unchanged const help to keep your data safe now you can write your own validation aware class and data type if schema encounter an instance of list tuple set or frozenset it will validate content of corresponding data container against all schema listed inside that container and aggregate all error if schema encounter an instance of dict it will validate data key value pair you can specify key a schema too this is useful if you want to check certain key value but don t care about others you can mark a key a optional a follows optional key can also carry a default to be used when no key in the data match default are used verbatim not passed through any validators specified in the value default can also be a callable also a caveat if you specify type schema won t validate the empty dict to do that you need schema or int int this is unlike what happens with list where schema int is valid will return true schema ha class and and or that help validating several schema for the same data in a dictionary you can also combine two key in a one or the other manner to do so use the or class a a key you can define hook which are function that are executed whenever a valid key value is found the forbidden class is an example of this you can mark a key a forbidden a follows a few thing are worth noting first the value paired with the forbidden key determines whether it will be rejected note if we hadn t supplied the age key here the call would have failed too but with schemawrongkeyerror not schemaforbiddenkeyerror second forbidden ha a higher priority than standard key and consequently than optional this mean we can do that you can also define your own hook the following hook will call my function if key is encountered here s an example where a deprecated class is added to log warning whenever a key is encountered the schema parameter ignore extra key cause validation to ignore extra key in a dictionary and also to not return them after validating if you would like any extra key returned use object object a one of the key value pair which will match any key and any value otherwise extra key will raise a schemaerror the schema validate method accepts additional keyword argument the keyword argument will be propagated to the validate method of any child validatables including any ad hoc schema object or the default value callable if a callable is specified for optional key this feature can be used together with inheritance of the schema class for customized validation here is an example where a post validation hook that run after validation against a sub schema in a larger schema note that the additional keyword argument is event schema is necessary to limit the customized behavior to the eventschema object itself so that it won t affect any recursive invoke of the self class validate for the child schema e g the call to schema capacity validate capacity you can pas a keyword argument error to any of validatable class such a schema and or regex use to report this error instead of a built in one you can see all error that occurred by accessing exception s exc auto for auto generated error message and exc error for error which had error text passed to them you can exit with sys exit exc code if you want to show the message to the user without traceback error message are given precedence in that case here is a quick example validation of create a gist request from github api assume you are using docopt with the following usage pattern usage my program py count n path file and you would like to validate that file are readable and that path exists and that count is either integer from to or none assuming docopt return the following dict this is how you validate it using schema a you can see schema validated data successfully opened file and converted to int you can also generate standard draft json schema from a dict schema this can be used to add word completion validation and documentation directly in code editor the output schema can also be used with json schema compatible library just define your schema normally and call json schema on it the output is a python dict you need to dump it to json you can add description for the schema element using the literal object instead of a string the main schema can also have a description these will appear in ides to help your user write a configuration the resulting json schema is not guaranteed to accept the same object a the library would accept since some validation are not implemented or have no json schema equivalent this is the case of the use and hook object for example use a dict literal the dict key are the json schema property example schema test str becomes type object property test type string required test description: cython implementation of the toolz package which provides high performance utility function for iterables function and dictionary toolz is a pure python package that borrows heavily from contemporary functional languanges it is designed to interoperate seamlessly with other library including itertools functools and third party library high performance functional data analysis is possible with builtin type like list and dict and user defined data structure and low memory usage is achieved by using the iterator protocol and returning iterators whenever possible cytoolz implement the same api a toolz the main difference are that cytoolz is faster typically x faster with a few spectacular exception and cytoolz offer a c api that is accessible to other project developed in cython since toolz is able to process very large potentially infinite data set the performance increase gained by using cytoolz can be significant see the pytoolz documentation at http toolz readthedocs io and the full api documentation for more detail new bsd see license file cytoolz is on the python package index pypi cytoolz support python with a common codebase it is developed in cython but requires no dependecies other than cpython and a c compiler like toolz it is a light weight dependency toolz and cytoolz aim to be a repository for utility function particularly those that come from the functional programming and list processing tradition we welcome contribution that fall within this scope and encourage user to scrape their util py file for function that are broadly useful please take a look at our issue page for toolz and cytoolz for contribution idea see our mailing list we re friendly

description: conll u parser par a conll u formatted string into a nested python dictionary conll u is often the output of natural language processing task note a of conllu python is required to install conllu see note on updating from to or if you are using conda conllu version drop support for python and all version of earlier than python if you need support for older version of python you can always pin your install to an old version of conllu you can install it with pip install conllu the universal dependency release changed two of the field name from xpostag xpos and upostag upos version of conllu handle this by aliasing the previous name to the new name this mean you can use xpos upos or xpostag upostag they will both return the same thing this doe change the public api slightly so i ve upped the major version to but i ve taken care to ensure you most likely do not have to update your code when you update to i don t like breaking backwards compatibility but to be able to add new feature i felt i had to this mean that updating from to might require code change here s a guide on how to upgrade to at the top level conllu provides two method parse and parse tree the first one par sentence and return a flat list the other return a nested tree structure let s go through them one by one now you have the data in a variable called data let s parse it advanced usage if you have many sentence say over a megabyte to parse at once you can avoid loading them into memory at once by using parse incr instead of parse it take an opened file and return a generator instead of the list directly so you need to either iterate over it or call list to get the tokenlists out here s how you would use it for most file parse work fine since one conll u file usually contains multiple sentence parse always return a list of sentence each sentence is represented by a tokenlist the tokenlist support indexing so you can get the first token represented by an ordered dictionary like this by using filter field field value you can filter based on subelements further down in a parsed token filter can also be chained meaning you can do sentence filter filter and filtering on multiple property at the same time sentence filter field value field value mean that all property must match you can also filter using a lambda function a value this is useful if you for instance would like to filter out only token with integer id s if you want to change your conll u file there are a couple of convenience method to know about you can add a new token by simply appending a dictionary with the field you want to a tokenlist changing a sentence just mean indexing into it and setting a value to what you want if you omit a field when passing in a dict conllu will fill in a for those value each sentence can also have metadata in the form of comment before the sentence start this is available in a property on the tokenlist called metadata if you ever want to get your conll u formated text back maybe after changing something use the serialize method you can also convert a tokenlist to a tokentree by using to tree that s it sometimes you re interested in the tree structure that hide in the head column of a conll u file when this is the case use parse tree to get a nested structure representing the sentence advanced usage if you have many sentence say over a megabyte to parse at once you can avoid loading them into memory at once by using parse tree incr instead of parse tree it take an opened file and return a generator instead of the list directly so you need to either iterate over it or call list to get the tokentrees out here s how you would use it since one conll u file usually contains multiple sentence parse tree always return a list of description: this package is a backport of the refreshed and enhanced configparser from later python version to use the backport instead of the built in version simply import it explicitly a a backport to use the backport on python and the built in version on python use the standard invocation for detailed documentation consult the vanilla version at http doc python org library configparser html whereas almost completely compatible with it older brother configparser sport a bunch of interesting new feature full mapping protocol access more info there s now one default configparser class which basically is the old safeconfigparser with a bunch of tweak which make it more predictable for user don t need interpolation simply use configparser interpolation none no need to use a distinct rawconfigparser anymore the parser is highly customizable upon instantiation supporting thing like changing option delimiters comment character the name of the default section the interpolation syntax etc you can easily create your own interpolation syntax but there are two powerful implementation built in more info the classic string like s syntax called basicinterpolation a new buildout like syntax called extendedinterpolation fallback value may be specified in getters more info configparser object can now read data directly from string and from dictionary that mean importing configuration from json or specifying default value for the whole configuration multiple section is now a single line of code same go for copying data from another configparser instance thanks to it mapping protocol support many smaller tweak update and fixesconfigparser come from python and a such it work well with unicode the library is generally cleaned up in term of internal data storage and reading writing file there are a couple of incompatibility with the old configparser due to that however the work required to migrate is well worth it a it show the issue that would likely come up during migration of your project to python the design assumes that unicode string are used whenever possible that give you the certainty that what s stored in a configuration object is text once your configuration is read the rest of your application doesn t have to deal with encoding issue all you have is text the only two phase when you should explicitly state encoding is when you either read from an external source e g a file or write back this project us semver to communicate the impact of various release while periodically syncing with the upstream implementation in cpython the history serf a a reference indicating which version incorporate which upstream functionality prior to the release another scheme wa used to associate the cpython and backports release this backport wa originally authored by ukasz langa the current vanilla configparser maintainer for cpython and is currently maintained by jason r coombs configparser repositoryconfigparser issue trackeravailable a part of the tidelift subscription this project and the maintainer of thousand of other package are working with tidelift to deliver one enterprise subscription that cover all of the open source you use learn more to report a security vulnerability please use the tidelift security contact tidelift will coordinate the fix and disclosure this section is technical and should bother you only if you are wondering how this backport is produced if the implementation detail of this backport are not important for you feel free to ignore the following content the project take the following branching approach the x branch hold unchanged file synchronized from the upstream cpython repository the synchronization is currently done by manually copying the required file and stating from which cpython changeset they come the main branch hold a version of the x code with some tweak that make it compatible with older python code on this branch must work on all supported python version test with tox or in ci the process work like this in the x branch run pip run sync upstream py which downloads the latest stable release of python and copy the relevant file from there into their new location and then commits those change with a nice reference to the relevant upstream commit hash check for new name in all and update import in configparser py accordingly commit merge the new commit to main run test commit make any compatibility change on main run test commit update the doc and release the new version to somewhat ease migration passing bytestrings is still supported but they are converted to unicode for internal storage anyway this mean that for the vast majority of string used in configuration file it won t matter if you pas them a bytestrings or unicode however if you pas a bytestring that cannot be converted to unicode using the naive ascii codec a unicodedecodeerror will be raised this is purposeful and help you manage proper encoding for all content you store in memory read from various source and write back life get much easier when you understand that you basically manage text in your application you don t care about byte but about letter in that regard the concept of content encoding is meaningless the only time when you deal with raw byte is when you write the data to a file then you have to specify how your text should be encoded on the other end to get meaningful text from a file the application reading it ha to know which encoding wa used during it creation but once the byte are read and properly decoded all you have is text this is especially powerful when you start interacting with multiple data source even if each of them us a different encoding inside your application data is held in abstract text form you can program your business logic without worrying about which data came from which source you can freely exchange the data you store between source only reading writing file requires encoding your text to byte

description: the coloredlogs package enables colored terminal output for python s logging module the coloredformatter class inherits from logging formatter and us ansi escape sequence to render your logging message in color it us only standard color so it should work on any unix terminal it s currently tested on python and pypy and on window coloredlogs automatically try to enable native ansi support on up to date window installation and fall back on using colorama if installed here is a screen shot of the demo that is printed when the command coloredlogs demo is executed note that the screenshot above includes custom logging level defined by my verboselogs package if you install both coloredlogs and verboselogs it will just work verboselogs is of course not required to use coloredlogs installationoptional dependenciesusageformat of log messagesenabling millisecond precisioncustom logging fieldschanging text style and colorscolored output from cronmodifying your crontabmodifying your python codecontactlicensethe coloredlogs package is available on pypi which mean installation should be a simple a there s actually a multitude of way to install python package e g the per user site package directory virtual environment or just installing system wide and i have no intention of getting into that discussion here so if this intimidates you then read up on your option before returning to these instruction native ansi support on window requires an up to date window installation if this is not working for you then consider installing the colorama package once colorama is installed it will be used automatically here s an example of how easy it is to get started the coloredformatter class support user defined log format so you can use any log format you like the default log format is a follows this log format result in the following output you can customize the log format and styling using environment variable a well a programmatically please refer to the online documentation for detail if you re switching from logging basicconfig to coloredlogs install you may notice that timestamps no longer include millisecond this is because coloredlogs doesn t output millisecond in timestamps unless you explicitly tell it to there are three way to do that the easy way is to pas the millisecond argument to coloredlogs install this became supported in release due to alternatively you can change the log format to include msec here s what the call to coloredlogs install would then look like customizing the log format also enables you to change the delimiter that separate second from millisecond the comma above this became possible in release which added support for user defined log format if the use of msec d isn t flexible enough you can instead add f to the date time format it will be replaced by the value of msec d support for the f directive wa added to release due to the following custom log format field are supported hostname s provides the hostname of the local system programname s provides the name of the currently running program username s provides the username of the currently logged in user when coloredlogs install detects that any of these field are used in the format string the applicable logging filter subclass are automatically registered to populate the relevant log record field the online documentation contains an example of customizing the text style and color when coloredlogs is used in a cron job the output that s e mailed to you by cron won t contain any ansi escape sequence because coloredlogs realizes that it s not attached to an interactive terminal if you d like to have color e mailed to you by cron there are two way to make it happen modifying your crontabmodifying your python codehere s an example of a minimal crontab the coloredlogs program is installed when you install the coloredlogs python package when you execute coloredlogs to html your command it run your command under the external program script you need to have this installed this make your command think that it s attached to an interactive terminal which mean it will output ansi escape sequence which will then be converted to html by the coloredlogs program yes this is a bit convoluted but it work great the coloredcronmailer class provides a context manager that automatically enables html output when the content type variable ha been correctly set in the crontab this requires my capturer package which you can install using pip install coloredlogs cron the cron extra will pull in capturer or newer which is required to capture the output while silencing it otherwise you d get duplicate output in the email sent by cron the context manager can also be used to retroactively silence output that ha already been produced this can be useful to avoid spammy cron job that have nothing useful to do but still email their output to the system administrator every few minute the latest version of coloredlogs is available on pypi and github the online documentation is available on read the doc and includes a changelog for bug report please create an issue on github if you have question suggestion etc feel free to send me an e mail at peter peterodding com this software is licensed under the mit license peter odding

description: an ast unparser for python this is a factored out version of unparse found in the python source distribution under demo parser in python and under tool parser in python basic example this library is single source compatible with python through python it is authored by the python core developer i have simply merged the python and the python source and test suite and added a wrapper this factoring out is to provide a library implementation that support both version added to this is a pretty printing dump utility function the test suite both run specific test and also roundtrips much of the standard library similar project include codegenastorastmonkeyastprintnone of these roundtrip much of the standard library and fail several of the basic test in the test unparse test suite this library us mature and core maintained code instead of trying to patch existing library the unparse and the test unparse module are under the psf license extension include typed astunparse extends astunparse to support type annotation documentation http astunparse rtfd org unparses python ast pretty print ast here s the recent change to ast unparser add full support for python add support for the constant node in python add test to the sdistfix the roundtripping of very complex f string python compatibilitypython compatibilitybugfix correct argparser option typesupport for the async keywordsupport for unparsing interactive and expression nodespython compatibilitypython through compatibilitya new function dump is added to return a pretty printed version of the ast it s also available when running python m astunparse a the dump argument unparse will return the source code for an ast it is pretty feature complete and round trip the stdlib and is compatible with python and python running python m astunparse will print the round tripped source for any python file given a argument

description: http pypi org project astor http astor readthedocs iohttps github com berkerpeksag astor clause bsdastor is designed to allow easy manipulation of python source via the ast there are some other similar library but astor focus on the following area round trip an ast back to python modified ast doesn t need linenumbers ctx etc or otherwise be directly compileable for the round trip to work easy to read generated code a well codecan round trip two different source tree to compare for functional difference using the astor rtrip tool for example after pep edits dump pretty printing of astharder to read than round tripped code but more accurate to figure out what is going on easier to read than dump from built in ast modulenon recursive treewalksometimes you want a recursive treewalk and astor support that starting at any node on the tree but sometimes you don t need to do that astor doesn t require you to explicitly visit sub node unless you want to you can add code that executes before a node s child are visited and oryou can add code that executes after a node s child are visited and oryou can add code that executes and keep the node s child from being visited and optionally visit them yourself via a recursive call write function to access the tree based on object name and or attribute namesenjoy easy access to parent node s for tree rewritingthe decompilation back to python is based on code originally written by armin ronacher armin s code wa well structured but failed on some obscure corner case of the python language and even more corner case when the ast changed on different version of python and it output arguably had cosmetic issue for example it produced parenthesis even in some case where they were not needed to avoid having to reason about precedence other derivative of armin s code are floating around and typically have fix for a few corner case that happened to be noticed by the maintainer but most of them have not been tested a thoroughly a astor one exception may be the version of codegen maintained at github by censoredusername this ha been tested to work properly on python using astor s test suite and a it is a single source file it may be easier to drop into some application that do not require astor s other feature or python x compatibility

description: traitlets is a pure python library enabling it implementation relies on the descriptor pattern and it is a lightweight pure python alternative of the trait library traitlets power the configuration system of ipython and jupyter and the declarative api of ipython interactive widget for a local installation make sure you have pip installed and run for a development installation clone this repository change into the traitlets root directory and run pip traitlets ha adopted automatic code formatting so you shouldn t need to worry too much about your code style a long a your code is valid the pre commit hook should take care of how it should look to install pre commit locally run the following you can invoke the pre commit hook by hand at any time with which should run any autoformatting on your code and tell you about any error it couldn t fix automatically you may also install black integration into your text editor to format code automatically if you have already committed file before setting up the pre commit hook with pre commit install you can fix everything up using pre commit run all file you need to make the fixing commit yourself after that some of the hook only run on ci by default but you can invoke them by running with the hook stage manual argument any class with trait attribute must inherit from hastraits for the list of available trait type and their property see the trait type section of the documentation to calculate a default value dynamically decorate a method of your class with default traitname this method will be called on the instance and should return the default value in this example the username default method is decorated with default username when a trait change an application can follow this trait change with additional action to do something when a trait attribute is changed decorate a method with traitlets observe the method will be called with a single argument a dictionary which contains an owner new value old value name of the changed trait and the event type in this example the num changed method is decorated with observe num and is passed the following dictionary when called each trait type int unicode dict etc may have it own validation or coercion logic in addition we can register custom cross validators that may depend on the state of other attribute for example however we recommend that custom cross validators don t modify the state of the hastraits instance release should be automatically build and pushed to pypi when a tag is marked and pushed to github

description: xmltodict is a python module that make working with xml feel like you are working with json a in this spec by default xmltodict doe no xml namespace processing it just treat namespace declaration a regular node attribute but passing process namespaces true will make it expand namespaces for you it also let you collapse certain namespaces to shorthand prefix or skip them altogether xmltodict is very fast expat based and ha a streaming mode with a small memory footprint suitable for big xml dump like discogs or wikipedia it can also be used from the command line to pipe object to a script like this or just cache the dicts so you don t have to parse that big xml file again you do this only once and you reuse the dicts with every script that need them you can also convert in the other direction using the unparse method text value for node can be specified with the cdata key key in the python dict while node property can be specified with the attr prefix prefixed to the key name in the python dict the default value for attr prefix is and the default value for cdata key is text list that are specified under a key in a dictionary use the key a a tag for each item but if a list doe have a parent key for example if a list exists inside another list it doe not have a tag to use and the item are converted to a string a shown in the example below to give tag to nested list use the expand iter keyword argument to provide a tag a demonstrated below note that using expand iter will break roundtripping you just need tothere is an official fedora package for xmltodict there is an official arch linux package for xmltodict there is an official debian package for xmltodict there is an official freebsd port for xmltodict there is an official opensuse package for xmltodict

description: the deprecation library provides a deprecated decorator and a fail if not removed decorator for your test together the two enable the automation of several thing the docstring of a deprecated method get the deprecation detail appended to the end of it if you generate your api doc direct from your source you don t need to worry about writing your own notification you also don t need to worry about forgetting to write it it s done for you rather than having code live on forever because you only deprecated it but never actually moved on from it you can have your test tell you when it s time to remove the code the deprecated decorator can be told when it s time to entirely remove the code which cause fail if not removed to raise an assertionerror causing either your unittest or py test test to fail see http deprecation readthedocs io for the full documentation yes by default since and for good reason and this work fine with that it often make sense for you to run your test with a w flag or the pythonwarnings environment variable so you catch warning in development and handle them appropriately the warning raised by this library show up there a they re subclass of the built in deprecationwarning see the command line and environment variable documentation for more detail even if you don t enable those thing the behavior of this library remains the same the docstrings will still be updated and the test will still fail when they need to you ll get the benefit regardless of what python care about deprecationwarning exposing application user to deprecationwarnings that are emitted by lower level code needlessly involves end user in how thing are done it often lead to user raising issue about warning they re presented which on one hand is done rightfully so a it s been presented to them a some sort of issue to resolve however at the same time the warning could be well known and planned for from either side loud deprecationwarnings can be seen a noise that isn t necessary outside of development

description: docstestspackagethis plugin produce coverage report compared to just using coverage run this plugin doe some extra subprocess support you can fork or run stuff in a subprocess and will get covered without any fuss xdist support you can use all of pytest xdist s feature and still get coverage consistent pytest behavior if you run coverage run m pytest you will have slightly different sys path cwd will be in it unlike when running pytest all feature offered by the coverage package should work either through pytest cov s command line option or through coverage s config file free software mit licenseinstall with pip for distributed testing support install pytest xdist pytest cov is using a new pth file pytest cov pth you may want to manually remove the older init cov core pth from site package a it s not automatically removed uninstall with pip under certain scenario a stray pth file may be left around in site package pytest cov may leave a pytest cov pth if you installed without wheel easy install setup py install etc pytest cov or older will leave a init cov core pth would produce a report like http pytest cov rtfd org the data file is erased at the beginning of testing to ensure clean data for each test run if you need to combine the coverage of several test run you can use the cov append option to append this coverage data to coverage data from previous test run the data file is left at the end of testing so that it is possible to use normal coverage tool to examine it for distributed testing the worker must have the pytest cov package installed this is needed since the plugin must be registered through setuptools for pytest to start the plugin on the worker for subprocess measurement environment variable must make it from the main process to the subprocess the python used by the subprocess must have pytest cov installed the subprocess must do normal site initialisation so that the environment variable can be detected and coverage started coverage plugins ned batchelder for coverage and it ability to combine the coverage result of parallel run holger krekel for pytest with it distributed testing support jason pellerin for nose michael description: any color you like black is the uncompromising python code formatter by using it you agree to cede control over minutia of hand formatting in return black give you speed determinism and freedom from pycodestyle nagging about formatting you will save time and mental energy for more important matter blackened code look the same regardless of the project you re reading formatting becomes transparent after a while and you can focus on the content instead black make code review faster by producing the smallest diffs possible try it out now using the black playground watch the pycon talk to learn more read the documentation on readthedocs black can be installed by running pip install black it requires python to run if you want to format jupyter notebook install with pip install black jupyter if you can t wait for the latest hotness and want to install from github use pip install git http github com psf blackto get started right away with sensible default you can run black a a package if running it a a script doesn t work further information can be found in our doc black is already successfully used by many project small and big black ha a comprehensive test suite with efficient parallel test and our own auto formatting and parallel continuous integration runner now that we have become stable you should not expect large formatting to change in the future stylistic change will mostly be response to bug report and support for new python syntax for more information please refer to the the black code style also a a safety measure which slows down processing black will check that the reformatted code still produce a valid ast that is effectively equivalent to the original see the pragmatism section for detail if you re feeling confident use fast black is a pep compliant opinionated formatter black reformats entire file in place style configuration option are deliberately limited and rarely added it doesn t take previous formatting into account see pragmatism for exception our documentation cover the current black code style but planned change to it are also documented they re both worth taking a look change to the black code style are bound by the stability policy please refer to this document before submitting an issue what seems like a bug might be intended behaviour early version of black used to be absolutist in some respect they took after it initial author this wa fine at the time a it made the implementation simpler and there were not many user anyway not many edge case were reported a a mature tool black doe make some exception to rule it otherwise hold please refer to this document before submitting an issue just like with the document above what seems like a bug might be intended behaviour black is able to read project specific default value for it command line option from a pyproject toml file this is especially useful for specifying custom include and exclude force exclude extend exclude pattern for your project you can find more detail in our documentation and if you re looking for more general configuration documentation pro tip if you re asking yourself do i need to configure anything the answer is no black is all about sensible default applying those default will have your code in compliance with many other black formatted project the following notable open source project trust black with enforcing a consistent code style pytest tox pyramid django django channel hypothesis attrs sqlalchemy poetry pypa application warehouse bandersnatch pipenv virtualenv panda pillow twisted localstack every datadog agent integration home assistant zulip kedro openoa floris orbit wombat and many more the following organization use black facebook dropbox keeptruckin mozilla quora duolingo quantumblack tesla are we missing anyone let u know mike bayer author of sqlalchemy i can t think of any single tool in my entire programming career that ha given me a bigger productivity increase by it introduction i can now do refactorings in about of the keystroke that it would have taken me previously when we had no way for code to format itself dusty phillips writer black is opinionated so you don t have to be hynek schlawack creator of attrs core developer of twisted and cpython an auto formatter that doesn t suck is all i want for xmas carl meyer django core developer at least the name is good kenneth reitz creator of request and pipenv this vastly improves the formatting of our code thanks a ton use the badge in your project s readme md using the badge in readme rst look like this mitwelcome happy to see you willing to make the project better you can get started by reading this you can also take a look at the rest of the contributing doc or talk with the developer the log ha become rather long it moved to it own file see change the author list is quite long nowadays so it life in it own file see author mdeveryone participating in the black project and in particular in the issue tracker pull request and social medium activity is expected to treat other people with respect and more generally to follow the guideline articulated in the python community code of conduct at the same time humor is encouraged in fact basic familiarity with monty python s flying circus is expected we are not savage and if you really need to slap somebody do it with a fish while dancing description: this is a python module for monitoring memory consumption of a process a well a line by line analysis of memory consumption for python program it is a pure python module which depends on the psutil module install via pip the package is also available on conda forge to install from source download the package extract and type the line by line memory usage mode is used much in the same way of the line profiler first decorate the function you would like to profile with profile and then run the script with a special script in this case with specific argument to the python interpreter in the following example we create a simple function my func that allocates list a b and then deletes b execute the code passing the option m memory profiler to the python interpreter to load the memory profiler module and print to stdout the line by line analysis if the file name wa example py this would result in output will follow the first column represents the line number of the code that ha been profiled the second column mem usage the memory usage of the python interpreter after that line ha been executed the third column increment represents the difference in memory of the current line with respect to the last one the last column line content print the code that ha been profiled a function decorator is also available use a follows in this case the script can be run without specifying m memory profiler in the command line in function decorator you can specify the precision a an argument to the decorator function use a follows if a python script with decorator profile is called using m memory profiler in the command line the precision parameter is ignored sometimes it is useful to have full memory usage report a a function of time not line by line of external process be it python script or not in this case the executable mprof might be useful use it like the first line run the executable and record memory usage along time in a file written in the current directory once it s done a graph plot can be obtained using the second line the recorded file contains a timestamps that allows for several profile to be kept at the same time help on each mprof subcommand can be obtained with the h flag e g mprof run h in the case of a python script using the previous command doe not give you any information on which function is executed at a given time depending on the case it can be difficult to identify the part of the code that is causing the highest memory usage adding the profile decorator to a function and running the python script withmprof run script will record timestamps when entering leaving the profiled function runningmprof plotafterward will plot the result making plot using matplotlib similar to these or with mprof plot flame the function and timestamp name will appear on hover a discussion of these capability can be found here warningif your python file import the memory profiler from memory profiler import profile these timestamps will not be recorded comment out the import leave your function decorated and re run the available command for mprof are mprof run running an executable recording memory usagemprof plot plotting one the recorded memory usage by default the last one mprof list listing all recorded memory usage file in a user friendly way mprof clean removing all recorded memory usage file mprof rm removing specific recorded memory usage filesin a multiprocessing context the main process will spawn child process whose system resource are allocated separately from the parent process this can lead to an inaccurate report of memory usage since by default only the parent process is being tracked the mprof utility provides two mechanism to track the usage of child process sum the memory of all child to the parent s usage and track each child individual to create a report that combine memory usage of all the child and the parent use the include child flag in either the profile decorator or a a command line argument to mprof the second method track each child independently of the main process serializing child row by index to the output stream use the multiprocess flag and plot a follows this will create a plot using matplotlib similar to this you can combine both the include child and multiprocess flag to show the total memory of the program a well a each child individually if using the api directly note that the return from memory usage will include the child memory in a nested list along with the main process memory by default the command line call is set a the graph title if you wish to customize it you can use the t option to manually set the figure title mprof plot t recorded memory usage you can also hide the function timestamps using the n flag such asmprof plot ntrend line and it numeric slope can be plotted using the s flag such asmprof plot sthe intended usage of the s switch is to check the label numerical slope over a significant time period for it might mean a memory leak if or near the memory usage may be considered stable to be interpreted depending on the expected process memory usage pattern also might mean that the sampling period is too small the trend line are for ilustrative purpose and are plotted a very small dashed line it is possible to set breakpoints depending on the amount of memory used that is you can specify a threshold and a soon a the program us more memory than what is specified in the threshold it will stop execution and run into the pdb debugger to use it you will have to decorate the function a done in the previous section with profile and then run your script with the option m memory profiler pdb mmem x where x is a number representing the memory threshold in mb for example will run my script py and step into the pdb debugger a soon a the code us more than mb in the decorated function memory profiler expose a number of function to be used in third party code memory usage proc interval timeout none return the memory usage over a time interval the first argument proc represents what should be monitored this can either be the pid of a process not necessarily a python program a string containing some python code to be evaluated or a tuple f args kw containing a function and it argument to be evaluated a f args kw for example here i ve told memory profiler to get the memory consumption of the current description: this module provides python binding for glfw on github glfw glfw it is a ctypes wrapper which keep very close to the original glfw api except for function name use the pythonic word with underscore notation instead of camelcaseglfw and glfw prefix have been removed a their function is replaced by the module namespace you can use from glfw glfw import if you prefer the naming convention used by the glfw c api structs have been replaced with python sequence and namedtuplesfunctions like glfwgetmonitors return a list instead of a pointer and an object countgamma ramp use float between and instead of unsigned short use glfw normalize gamma ramp false to disable this glfw error are reported a glfw glfwerror warning if no error callback is set use glfw error reporting false to disable this set it to warn instead to issue warning set it to log to log it using the glfw logger or set it to a dict to define the behavior for specific error code instead of a sequence for glfwimage structs pil pillow image object can be usedpyglfw can be installed using pip the glfw shared library and visual c runtime are included in the python wheel to use a different glfw library you can set pyglfw library to it location the glfw shared library for bit is included in the python wheel for macos if you are using a bit python installation or otherwise cannot use the library downloaded with the wheel you can build and install it yourself by compiling glfw from source use dbuild shared libs on pyglfw will search for the library in a list of search path including those in dyld library path if you want to use a specific library you can set the pyglfw library environment variable to it path the glfw shared library is included in the python wheel for linux if you cannot use these on your system you can install the glfw shared library using a package management system e g apt install libglfw on debian or ubuntu or you can build and install it yourself by compiling glfw from source use dbuild shared libs on pyglfw will search for the library in a list of search path including those in ld library path if you want to use a specific library you can set the pyglfw library environment variable to it path if you are using the development version of glfw and would like to use wrapper for currently unreleased macro and function you can instead install or set the pyglfw preview environment variable note however that there will be a slight delay between the development version of glfw and the wrapper provided by this package the example from the glfw documentation ported to pyglfw

description: pyrsistent is a number of persistent collection by some referred to a functional data structure persistent in the sense that they are immutable all method on a data structure that would normally mutate it instead return a new copy of the structure containing the requested update the original structure is left untouched this will simplify the reasoning about what a program doe since no hidden side effect ever can take place to these data structure you can rest assured that the object you hold a reference to will remain the same throughout it lifetime and need not worry that somewhere five stack level below you in the darkest corner of your application someone ha decided to remove that element that you expected to be there pyrsistent is influenced by persistent data structure such a those found in the standard library of clojure the data structure are designed to share common element through path copying it aim at taking these concept and make them a pythonic a possible so that they can be easily integrated into any python program without hassle if you want use literal syntax to define them in your code rather than function call check out pyrthon be aware that one is experimental unmaintained and alpha software the collection type and key feature currently implemented are pvector similar to a python listpmap similar to dictpset similar to setprecord a pmap on steroid with fixed field optional type and invariant checking and much morepclass a python class fixed field optional type and invariant checking and much morechecked collection pvector pmap and pset with optional type and invariance check and morepbag similar to collection counterplist a classic singly linked listpdeque similar to collection dequeimmutable object type immutable built on the named tuplefreeze and thaw function to convert between python standard collection and pyrsistent collection flexible transformation of arbitrarily complex structure built from pmaps and pvectors below are example of common usage pattern for some of the structure and feature more information and full documentation for all data structure is available in the documentation with full support for the sequence protocol pvector is meant a a drop in replacement to the built in list from a reader point of view write operation of course differ since no in place mutation is done but naming should be in line with corresponding operation on the built in list support for the hashable protocol also mean that it can be used a key in mapping appends are amortized o random access and insert is log n where n is the size of the vector with full support for the mapping protocol pmap is meant a a drop in replacement to the built in dict from a reader point of view support for the hashable protocol also mean that it can be used a key in other mapping random access and insert is log n where n is the size of the map with full support for the set protocol pset is meant a a drop in replacement to the built in set from a reader point of view support for the hashable protocol also mean that it can be used a key in mapping random access and insert is log n where n is the size of the set a precord is a pmap with a fixed set of specified field record are declared a python class inheriting from precord because it is a pmap it ha full support for all mapping method such a iteration and element access using subscript notation it is possible to add type information to the record to enforce type check multiple allowed type can be specified by providing an iterable of type custom type class that are iterable should be wrapped in a tuple to prevent their member being added to the set of valid type although enums in particular are now supported without wrapping see for more information field are not mandatory by default but can be specified a such if field are missing an invariantexception will be thrown which contains information about the missing field it is possible to add invariant that must hold when evolving the record invariant can be specified on both field and record level if invariant fail an invariantexception will be thrown which contains information about the failing invariant an invariant function should return a tuple consisting of a boolean that tell if the invariant hold or not and an object describing the invariant this object can later be used to identify which invariant that failed the global invariant function is only executed if all field invariant hold global invariant are inherited to subclass invariant may also contain multiple assertion for those case the invariant function should return a tuple of invariant tuples a described above this structure is reflected in the invariant error attribute of the exception which will contain tuples with data from all failed invariant eg it s possible to specify factory function for field the factory function receives whatever is supplied a field value and the actual returned by the factory is assigned to the field given that any type and invariant check hold precords have a default factory specified a a static function on the class create it take a mapping a argument and return an instance of the specific record if a record ha field of type precord the create method of that record will be called to create the sub record if no factory ha explicitly been specified to override this behaviour it is also possible to have field with pyrsistent collection precords support serialization back to dicts default serialization will take key and value a is and output them into a dict it is possible to specify custom serialization function to take care of field that require special treatment a pclass is a python class with a fixed set of specified field pclasses are declared a python class inheriting from pclass it is defined the same way that precords are and behaves like a precord in all aspect except that it is not a pmap and hence not a collection but rather a plain python object checked collection currently come in three flavor checkedpvector checkedpmap and checkedpset transformation are inspired by the cool library instar for clojure they let you evolve pmaps and pvectors with arbitrarily deep complex nesting using simple syntax and flexible matching syntax the first argument to transformation is the path that point out the value to transform the second is the transformation to perform if the transformation is callable it will be applied to the value s matching the path the path may also contain callables in that case they are treated a matcher if the matcher return true for a specific key it is considered for transformation pvector pmap and pset all have support for a concept dubbed evolvers an evolver act like a mutable view of the underlying persistent data structure with transaction like semantics no update of the original data structure is ever performed it is still fully immutable the evolvers have a very limited api by design to discourage excessive and inappropriate usage a that would take u down the mutable road in principle only basic mutation and element access function are supported check out the documentation of each data structure for specific example example of when you may want to use an evolver instead of working directly with the data structure include multiple update are done to the same data structure and the intermediate result are of no interest in this case using an evolver may be a more efficient and easier to work with you need to pas a vector into a legacy function or a function that you have no control over which performs in place mutation in this case pas an evolver instance instead and then create a new pvector from the evolver once the function return these function are great when your cozy immutable world ha to interact with the evil mutable world outside by default freeze will also recursively convert value inside pvectors and pmaps this behaviour can be changed by providing freeze with the flag strict false in this regard thaw operates a the inverse of freeze so will thaw value inside native data structure unless passed the strict false flag pyrsistent is developed and tested on python and pypy pyrsistent is developed with performance in mind still while some operation are nearly on par with their built in mutable counterpart in term of speed other operation are slower in the case where attempt at optimization have been done speed ha generally been valued over space pyrsistent come with two api compatible flavor of pvector on which pmap and pset are based one pure python implementation and one implemented a a c extension the latter generally being time faster than the former the c extension will be used automatically when possible the pure python implementation is fully pypy compatible running it under pypy speed operation up considerably if the structure are used heavily if jited for some case the performance is almost on par with the built in counterpart pep style type hint for use with mypy and various editor are available for most type and function in pyrsistent type class for annotating your own code with pyrsistent type are also available under pyrsistent typing pip install pyrsistentavailable at http pyrsistent readthedocs org brief presentation available at http slide com tobiasgustafsson immutability and python tobias description: the python keyring library provides an easy way to access the system keyring service from python it can be used in any application that need safe password storage these recommended implementation are available through third party backends on linux the kwallet backend relies on dbus python which doe not always install correctly when using pip compilation is needed for best result install dbus python a a system package macos keychain support macos big sur and later requires python or later with the universal binary see for detail the basic usage of keyring is pretty simple just call keyring set password and keyring get password keyring supply a keyring command which is installed with the package after installing keyring in most environment the command should be available for from python like so the python keyring lib contains implementation for several backends the library will attempt to automatically choose the most suitable backend for the current environment user may description: provides a python interface to gpu management and monitoring function this is a wrapper around the nvml library for information about the nvml library see the nvml developer page http developer nvidia com nvidia management library nvmlas of version the nvml wrapper used in pynvml are identical to those published through nvidia ml py note that this file can be run with python m doctest v readme txt although the result are system dependentpython or an earlier version with the ctypes module you can use the lower level nvml bindingsor the higher level nvidia smi apipython method wrap nvml function implemented in a c shared library each function s use is the same with the following exception instead of returning error code failing error code are raised a python exception c function output parameter are returned from the corresponding python function left to right c structs are converted into python class python handle string buffer creation for usage information see the nvml documentation all meaningful nvml constant and enums are exposed in python the nvml value not available constant is not used instead none is mapped to the field many of the pynvml wrapper assume that the underlying nvidia management library nvml api can be used without admin root privilege however it is certainly possible for the system permission to prevent pynvml from querying gpu performance counter for example a simple way to check the permission status is to look for rmprofilingadminonly in the driver params file note that rmprofilingadminonly mean that admin sudo access is required for more information on setting unsetting the relevant admin privilege see these note on resolving err nvgpuctrperm error

description: pysoundfile is an audio library based on libsndfile cffi and numpy full documentation is available on http pysoundfile readthedocs org pysoundfile can read and write sound file file reading writing is supported through libsndfile which is a free cross platform open source lgpl library for reading and writing many different sampled sound file format that run on many platform including window o x and unix it is accessed through cffi which is a foreign function interface for python calling c code cffi is supported for cpython x and pypy pysoundfile represents audio data a numpy array pysoundfile ha evolved rapidly during the last few release most notably we changed the import name from import pysoundfile to import soundfile in in we cleaned up many small inconsistency particularly in the the ordering and naming of function argument and the removal of the indexing interface in we changed the default value of always d from true to false also the order of argument of the write function changed from write data file to write file data in we changed the ctype argument of the buffer method to dtype using the numpy dtype notation the old ctype argument still work but are now officially deprecated pysoundfile depends on the python package cffi and numpy and the system library libsndfile to install the python dependency i recommend using the anaconda distribution of python this will come with all dependency pre installed to install the dependency manually you can use the conda package manager which will install all dependency using conda install cffi numpy conda is also available independently of anaconda with pip install conda conda init with cffi and numpy installed you can use pip install pysoundfile to download and install the latest release of pysoundfile on window and o x this will also install the library libsndfile on linux you need to install libsndfile using your distribution s package manager for example sudo apt get install libsndfile data can be written to the file using soundfile write or read from the file using soundfile read pysoundfile can open all file format that libsndfile support for example wav flac ogg and mat file here is an example for a program that read a wave file and copy it into an ogg vorbis file sound file can also be read in short optionally overlapping block with soundfile block for example this calculates the signal level for each block of a long file sound file can also be opened a soundfile soundfile object every soundfile ha a specific sample rate data format and a set number of channel if a file is opened it is kept open for a long a the soundfile object exists the file close when the object is garbage collected but you should use the soundfile soundfile close method or the description: mwparserfromhell the mediawiki parser from hell is a python package that provides an easy to use and outrageously powerful parser for mediawiki wikicode it support python developed by earwig with contribution from legoktm and others full documentation is available on readthedocs development occurs on github the easiest way to install the parser is through the python package index you can install the latest release with pip install mwparserfromhell get pip make sure your pip is up to date first especially on window alternatively get the latest development version the comprehensive unit testing suite requires pytest pip install pytest and can be run with python m pytest normal usage is rather straightforward where text is page text wikicode is a mwparserfromhell wikicode object which act like an ordinary str object with some extra method for example since node can contain other node getting nested template is trivial you can also pas recursive false to filter template and explore template manually this is possible because node can contain additional wikicode object template can be easily modified to add remove or alter params wikicode object can be treated like list with append insert remove replace and more they also have a match method for comparing page or template name which take care of capitalization and whitespace you can then convert code back into a regular str object for saving the page by calling str on it while the mediawiki parser generates html and ha access to the content of template among other thing mwparserfromhell act a a direct interface to the source code only this ha several implication syntax element produced by a template transclusion cannot be detected for example imagine a hypothetical page template end bold that contained the text b while mediawiki would correctly understand that b foobar end bold translates to b foobar b mwparserfromhell ha no way of examining the content of end bold instead it would treat the bold tag a unfinished possibly extending further down the page template adjacent to external link a in http example com foo are considered part of the link in reality this would depend on the content of the template when different syntax element cross over each other a in echo hello world the parser get confused because this cannot be represented by an ordinary syntax tree instead the parser will treat the first syntax construct a plain text in this case only the italic tag would be properly parsed workaround since this commonly occurs with text formatting and text formatting is often not of interest to user you may pas skip style tag true to mwparserfromhell parse this treat and a plain text a future version of mwparserfromhell may include multiple parsing mode to get around this restriction more sensibly additionally the parser lack awareness of certain wiki specific setting word ending link are not supported since the linktrail rule are language specific localized namespace name aren t recognized so file link such a file are treated a regular wikilinks anything that look like an xml tag is treated a a tag even if it is not a recognized tag name since the list of valid tag depends on loaded mediawiki extension mwparserfromhell is used by and originally developed for earwigbot page object have a parse method that essentially call mwparserfromhell parse on page get if you re using pywikibot your code might look like this if you re not using a library you can parse any page with the following python code using the api and the request library
